# **Deployment and Evaluation of Snort Intrusion Detection System**

# **1\. Executive Summary**

This report presents the deployment and testing of the Snort Intrusion Detection System (IDS) in a virtual environment. The aim of the project is to understand how an IDS operates, how Snort can be installed and configured, and how it detects suspicious network activities such as ICMP ping requests and Nmap scanning techniques

The deployment was carried out using three virtual machines: an Ubuntu system running Snort as the IDS, a Kali Linux system acting as the attacker, and a Metasploitable 2 system serving as the target. Custom Snort rules were written to detect reconnaissance activities, and controlled attack simulations were performed to validate detection capabilities

The results showed that Snort successfully detected ICMP and Nmap-based scans in real time, demonstrating its effectiveness as a passive monitoring and alerting tool. This project provides practical, hands-on experience that reflects how Snort can be deployed in real organizational environments for network security monitoring.

## **2\. Introduction**

In today’s networks, organizations face constant threats such as scanning, probing, and attacks from unauthorized users. An Intrusion Detection System (IDS) helps security teams identify these threats by monitoring network traffic and raising alerts when suspicious activity is detected

This report explains, in simple terms, how **Snort**, an open‑source IDS, was installed and deployed in a **virtual environment**. The goal was to understand how Snort works, how it is installed, how rules are added, and how it detects basic attacks such as **ping (ICMP)** and **Nmap scans**.

The setup was done in a controlled and authorized virtual environment to simulate how Snort would work in a real organization

## **3\. Objectives**

The main purpose of this project was to:

1. Learn how to install and configure Snort  
2. Understand how an IDS monitors traffic without attacking systems  
3. Detect basic reconnaissance activities such as ICMP pings and Nmap scans  
4. Gain hands‑on experience that reflects real‑world IDS deployment

## **4\. Environment Overview**

### **4.1 Virtual Infrastructure**

Three virtual machines were used, and each one had a clear role:

| Machines | Operating System | Roles | IP addresses |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| IDS Server | Ubuntu | Snort IDS | 192.168.89.129 |
| Attacker | Kali Linux | Nmap and attack simulation | 192.168.89.131 |
| Target | Metasploitable 2 | Vulnerable host | 192.168.89.130 |

All machines were connected to the same virtual network. This allowed the Snort machine to see the traffic moving between the attacker and the target, similar to how an IDS watches traffic in a real organization

              Virtual Network (192.168.89.0/24)

        \------------------------------------------------

        ┌────────────────────┐

        │     Attacker        │

        │     Kali Linux      │

        │ 192.168.89.131      │

                  │  Scan / Attack Traffic

                  ▼

        ┌────────────────────┐

        │      Target         │

### **4.2 Network Configuration**

1. Network Type: Internal / Host-only virtual network  
2. IP Address Range: 192.168.89.0/24  
3. IDS Interface: Configured in promiscuous mode to capture all visible traffic

## **5\. Snort Installation and Configuration**

### **5.1 Preparing the System**

Before installing Snort, I made sure that my Ubuntu system was updated to make sure all packages were current using:

sudo apt update 

sudo apt upgrade \-y

The network interfaces were checked to identify the correct interface used for monitoring:

ifconfig

### **4.2 Installing Snort**

I installed snort using the Ubuntu package manager:

sudo apt install snort \-y  
![][image1]

During installation, the system asked for the local network range. This information helps Snort understand which network it is protecting.

![][image2]

After installation, I check for the version of Snort I installed:

snort \- \-version

![][image3]

## **5\. Configuring Snort**

### **5.1 Basic Configuration**

The main Snort configuration file is located at:

/etc/snort/snort.conf  
![][image4]

The protected network was defined using the following settings:

ipvar HOME\_NET 192.168.89.0/24  
ipvar EXTERNAL\_NET any

Snort was also configured to load custom rules from the local rules file:

include $RULE\_PATH/local.rules

![][image5]

### **5.2 Monitoring Interface Setup**

To make Snort behave like a real IDS, the monitoring network interface was placed in **promiscuous mode**. This allows Snort to see all traffic on the network:

sudo ip link set ens33 promisc on

sudo ip link set ens33 up

No IP address was assigned to this interface. This ensures Snort only listens and does not interact with the network.

## **6\. Writing Detection Rules**

Snort uses rules to decide what traffic is suspicious. I created a new folder for each rules

### **6.1 ICMP (Ping) Detection Rule**

This rule detects when a system sends ping requests:

alert icmp any any \-\> any any (itype:8; msg:”ICMP Ping Detected”; sid: 1000001; rev:1;). 

![][image6]

### **6.2 Nmap Scan Detection Rules**

Nmap scans use special TCP flag combinations. Snort rules were written to detect these patterns

alert tcp any any \-\> any any (flags:s; msg:”Nmap SYN Scan Detected”; flags:S; sid: 1000002; rev:1;)

![][image7]

### **6.3 hping3 Scan Detection Rules**

hping3 is a packet-crafting tool that allows an attacker to manually create and send customized network packets. Detection is therefore based on identifying **abnormal or suspicious packet behavior** rather than the tool itself

alert tcp any any \-\> any any (msg:”Possible hping3 Traffic”; flags:0; sid:1000003; rev:1;)

![][image8]

### **6.4 SSH Scan Detection Rules**

SSH scans target TCP port 22 to identify systems offering remote access services. Snort rules were implemented to detect TCP SYN packets directed at the SSH port.

alert tcp any any \-\> any 22 (flags:S; msg:"SSH connection attempt"; sid:1000010; rev:1;)

alert tcp any any \-\> any 22 (flags:S; threshold:type both, track by\_src, count 5, seconds 60; msg:"SSH brute force attempt detected"; sid:1000011; rev:1;)

alert tcp any any \-\> $HOME\_NET 22 (flags:S; threshold:type both, track by\_src, count 10, seconds 30; msg:"SSH scan detected"; sid:1000012; rev:1;)

alert tcp any any \-\> any 22 (msg:"SSH banner detected"; content:"SSH-"; depth:4; sid:1000013; rev:1;)

alert tcp any any \-\> any \!22 (content:"SSH-"; depth:4; msg:"SSH on non-standard port detected"; sid:1000014; rev:1;)

![][image9]

## **7\. Running Snort**

I started Snort in IDS mode using the following command:

sudo snort \-A console \-q \-c /etc/snort/snort.conf \-i ens33

Once started, Snort waits silently and only displays output when suspicious traffic is detected.

## **8\. Testing and Results**

### **8.1 ICMP Scan Detection Test**

#### **Test Description**

This test was performed to evaluate the ability of the deployed Snort Intrusion Detection System (IDS) to detect ICMP-based reconnaissance activity. ICMP scans are commonly used by attackers to determine whether a host is reachable and active on a network.

The IDS was configured with custom ICMP detection rules and set to monitor live network traffic in real time

#### **Test Execution**

An ICMP echo request (ping) was initiated from the attacker system toward the target machine. Although the attacker terminal displayed “Destination Host Unreachable” messages, ICMP packets were still transmitted across the network

![][image10]

#### **Result**

During the test, Snort successfully generated multiple alerts indicating ICMP echo request activity. The alerts were displayed in real time on the IDS console and clearly showed ICMP traffic between the attacker and the target.

Sample alert output:

\[\*\*\] ICMP Ping Detected \[\*\*\]

\[Priority: 0\] {ICMP} Attacker → Target

![][image11]

#### **Analysis**

The alerts confirm that Snort analyzes network traffic passively and does not depend on successful communication between the attacker and the target. Even though the target did not respond to the ICMP requests, the IDS was still able to detect and log the reconnaissance attempt.

This behavior is important in real-world environments, as attackers often probe systems that are protected by firewalls or configured to drop ICMP responses

### **8.2 Nmap Scan Detection Test**

### **Test Description**

This test was conducted to evaluate the effectiveness of the Snort Intrusion Detection System in detecting TCP-based reconnaissance activities generated by Nmap. Nmap is commonly used by attackers to identify open ports and running services on a target system before launching further attacks.

Custom Snort rules were configured to detect Nmap SYN scan behavior by monitoring abnormal TCP flag patterns and rapid connection attempts

### **Test Execution**

A TCP SYN scan was initiated against the target system using Nmap. The scan probed multiple TCP ports in quick succession to determine which services were available. This activity generated a large number of SYN packets, which are characteristic of reconnaissance scans.

At the same time, Snort was running in IDS mode and actively monitoring the network interface for suspicious traffic

![][image12]

### **Result**

During the scan, Snort successfully generated multiple real-time alerts indicating the detection of an Nmap SYN scan. The alerts showed repeated TCP SYN packets originating from the scanning host and targeting multiple ports on the destination system.

Sample alert output:

\[\*\*\] Nmap SYN Scan Detected \[\*\*\]

\[Priority: 0\] {TCP} Attacker → Target

The alerts were triggered continuously as the scan progressed, confirming that the detection rule functioned as intended

![][image13]

### **Analysis**

The volume and frequency of the alerts demonstrate that Snort was able to recognize the scanning pattern associated with Nmap SYN scans. Each alert corresponded to a TCP SYN packet sent to a different port, which aligns with standard Nmap scanning behavior.

This confirms that the IDS can effectively identify reconnaissance attempts even before any exploit or payload delivery occurs

### **8.3 hping3 Scan Test**

### **Test Description**

This test was conducted to evaluate the effectiveness of the Snort Intrusion Detection System (IDS) in detecting packet-crafting and low-level network attack activity generated using the hping3 tool. hping3 is commonly used by attackers to craft custom TCP/UDP packets for reconnaissance, firewall testing, and denial-of-service attack preparation.

Custom Snort rules were configured to identify hping3-generated traffic patterns

### **Test Execution**

During the test, the hping3 tool was used to send crafted packets toward the target system. The packets were transmitted at a rapid rate, simulating abnormal network behavior associated with packet manipulation and scanning activities.

The IDS was actively running and monitoring the network interface in real time during the attack simulation

![][image14]

### **Result**

Snort successfully detected the crafted traffic generated by hping3. Multiple alerts were triggered and displayed on the IDS console, indicating the presence of suspicious UDP packet activity.

Sample alert output:

\[\*\*\] HPING3 UDP packet detected \[\*\*\]

\[Priority: 0\] {UDP} Attacker → Target

The repeated alerts confirm that Snort identified the high-frequency and non-standard packet behavior produced by the hping3 tool

![][image15]

### **Analysis**

The detection of hping3 traffic demonstrates that Snort can identify packet-crafting attacks based on protocol behavior and traffic patterns rather than relying on application-layer signatures alone. The repeated nature of the alerts highlights the IDS’s ability to detect abnormal packet rates commonly associated with reconnaissance and denial-of-service preparation

This capability is critical for early-stage attack detection, as tools like hping3 are often used prior to more severe exploitation attempts

### **Conclusion**

The hping3 detection test was successful. Snort accurately identified and alerted on crafted UDP packets generated by the hping3 tool, confirming that the packet-crafting detection rules were correctly implemented and effective in identifying malicious network behavior

### **8.4 SSH Scan Detection Test**

### **Test Description**

This test was conducted to assess the ability of the Snort Intrusion Detection System (IDS) to detect Secure Shell (SSH) scanning and connection attempts. SSH is a commonly targeted service due to its widespread use for remote administration, making it a frequent target for reconnaissance and brute-force attacks

Custom Snort rules were configured to detect SSH connection attempts and Nmap-based SSH scans

### **Test Execution**

An SSH scan was initiated from the attacker system using the Nmap tool with the SSH script enabled. The scan specifically targeted the SSH service on the target machine to determine whether the port was open and accepting connections.

During the scan, the Snort IDS was actively running in console alert mode and monitoring the network interface in real time

![][image16]

### **Result**

Snort successfully detected both the SSH connection attempt and the associated Nmap scanning activity. Alerts were generated and displayed on the IDS console immediately after the scan was executed.

Sample alert output:

\[\*\*\] SSH connection attempt \[\*\*\]  
\[Priority: 0\] {TCP} Attacker → Target :22

\[\*\*\] Nmap SYN scan detected \[\*\*\]  
\[Priority: 0\] {TCP} Attacker → Target :22

The alerts confirm that Snort identified the reconnaissance activity directed at the SSH service

![][image17]

### **Analysis**

The detection of both SSH connection attempts and Nmap SYN scan activity demonstrates Snort’s effectiveness in identifying service-specific reconnaissance. The IDS successfully correlated TCP SYN packets and SSH connection behavior, indicating that the configured rules were capable of detecting early-stage attack attempts targeting SSH services

This type of detection is critical, as attackers often begin exploitation by scanning for exposed SSH services before launching brute-force or credential-based attacks

### **Conclusion**

The SSH scan detection test was successful. Snort accurately detected SSH-related reconnaissance activity and generated timely alerts, confirming that the SSH detection rules were properly implemented and functioning as intended

## **9\. Conclusion**

This project successfully demonstrated how Snort can be installed, configured, and used as an Intrusion Detection System. By detecting ICMP and Nmap scans, the lab provided a clear understanding of how IDS tools help organizations identify early signs of attacks. The knowledge gained from this project can be applied to real‑world security environments.
